      id: 2,
      documentId: 'mx12788wgyfuwb6jenak20n6',
      title: 'Understanding Enums in Node.js: Features and Advantages',
      slug: 'understanding-enums-in-nodejs-features-and-advantages',
      views: 0,
      description:
        '# Understanding Enums in Node.js: Features and Advantages\n\n### Introduction\n\nWhen building applications in Node.js, developers often need to work with a set of predefined constant values. For example, user roles (`admin`, `editor`, `viewer`) or order statuses (`pending`, `completed`, `canceled`).\nInstead of using plain strings or numbers everywhere, **Enums** help us define and organize such values in a clean and structured way.\n\n---\n\n## What is an Enum?\n\nAn **Enum (short for â€œenumerationâ€)** is a special data structure that represents a group of constant values.\nAlthough JavaScript (and Node.js) doesnâ€™t have built-in enums like TypeScript, we can implement them using:\n\n* **Objects**\n* **Frozen objects (`Object.freeze`)**\n* **TypeScript Enums** (if using TypeScript in Node.js projects)\n\n---\n\n## Example: Enum in Node.js with Objects\n\n```js\nconst UserRole = {\n  ADMIN: "admin",\n  EDITOR: "editor",\n  VIEWER: "viewer"\n};\n\nconsole.log(UserRole.ADMIN); // "admin"\n```\n\nTo make it immutable (unchangeable):\n\n```js\nconst UserRole = Object.freeze({\n  ADMIN: "admin",\n  EDITOR: "editor",\n  VIEWER: "viewer"\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Using Enums in TypeScript (Node.js + TS)\n\nTypeScript provides native support for enums:\n\n```ts\nenum OrderStatus {\n  Pending = "PENDING",\n  Completed = "COMPLETED",\n  Canceled = "CANCELED"\n}\n\nconsole.log(OrderStatus.Pending); // "PENDING"\n```\n\nThis is more powerful since TypeScript gives type safety and autocomplete.\n\n---\n\n## Features of Enums in Node.js\n\nâœ… **Readability** â€“ Code becomes more self-explanatory (no more â€œmagic stringsâ€).\nâœ… **Maintainability** â€“ Centralized place for all related constants.\nâœ… **Type Safety (with TS)** â€“ Prevents using invalid values.\nâœ… **Immutability** â€“ With `Object.freeze`, enums canâ€™t be modified accidentally.\nâœ… **Consistency** â€“ Ensures same values are used across the project.\n\n---\n\n## Advantages of Using Enums\n\n1. **Cleaner Code**\n   Instead of repeating `"admin"` everywhere, we just use `UserRole.ADMIN`.\n\n2. **Fewer Bugs**\n   Typos like `"admn"` wonâ€™t break the code because enum values are fixed.\n\n3. **Easier Refactoring**\n   If `"admin"` changes to `"administrator"`, update it once in the enum.\n\n4. **Improved Collaboration**\n   Teams understand roles/statuses faster when they see enums instead of random strings.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nEnums in Node.js help developers write **cleaner, safer, and more maintainable code**.\nEven though JavaScript doesnâ€™t natively support enums, we can implement them using **objects and `Object.freeze`**, or switch to **TypeScript enums** for stronger type checking.\n\nðŸ‘‰ If your project is small, objects with constants are enough.\nðŸ‘‰ For larger applications, **TypeScript enums** are highly recommended.\n\n---\n\nAsilbek, xohlaysanmi men senga shu blogga **real-life example** qilib `UserRole` va `OrderStatus` bilan login/register system code yozib koâ€˜rsatib beray?\n',
